Malindi Airport will receive an allocation of Sh. 1.5 billion in the 2017/2018 financial year to implement the ongoing expansion works of the facility to international Standards, parliamentary committee on transport and housing said on Friday.The parliamentary committee said the airport got Sh. 438 million in this financial year which ends in June.Kenya Airports Authority has projected the grand expansion plans of the airport shall cost a tune of about Sh. 6.6 Billion in long term to reach the international status.Transport Parliamentary committee members led by chairman and Mandera West MP Maalim Mahamud, Ganze MP Peter Shehe, Nyakach MP Aduma Awuor and Kacheliba MP Mark Lomulokol Lomunokoi had toured the airport which is undergoing major expansion work to see the progress and come out with recommendations.The chairman said they were satisfied with the progress of work done and asked the Ministry to FastTrack the development so as to boost the economy of Malindi.Speaking to journalists after touring the facility on Friday he said the government was committed to ensure that the project proceeds without any delays.&ldquo;We are satisfied with the progress of the airport, the government is keen on seeing the project goes on without any delays,&rsquo;&rsquo; he said.The legislators were first given a presentation of the expansion plan by the Airport manager Walter Agong .In the plan Agong said KAA is almost through with the first phase of the expansion of the airport.He said the ultramodern terminal building is already complete together with the new tower all which is fit with modern facilities required.At the same time he said the new apron, modern car park, and security fence were 95 percent complete.&ldquo;In our master plan we intend to make Malindi the best international airport, we are targeting the European market particularly the Italians, there has been a huge cry on the need to expand the airport,&rsquo;&rsquo; he said.Once complete he said the airport will be able to accommodate Airbus 319, 737 or 600 which can take off from Rome to Malindi nonstop.For the airport to be expanded fully the manager said they require 259 ha and the authorities have only 100.6 ha which means there was 159 hectares which should be acquired.Already the National Government dispatched Sh. 300 million to compensate land owners and squatters within the south of the airport a process which will be done by National Lands Commission and set to be complete by April this year.However the great challenge remains in expansion of the runway from 1.4 kilometers to 2.5 kilometers.Currently the Malindi airport manager said surveyors were on the ground marking the areas which will be affected before they begin negotiations with the affected people.